 ">full entry</a></span></span></span></div><div class="collapse" hclass="collapse" htag="div"><span class="unbox" id="adjective_unbox_3" unbox="wordorigin"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">late Middle English: from Old French <span class="ei">adjectif</span>, <span class="ei">-ive</span>, from Latin <span class="ei">adject-</span> ‘added’, from the verb <span class="ei">adicere</span>, from <span class="ei">ad-</span> ‘towards’ + <span class="ei">jacere</span> ‘throw’. The term was originally used in the phrase <span class="ei">noun adjective</span>, translating Latin <span class="ei">nomen adjectivum</span>, a translation of Greek <span class="ei">onoma epitheton</span> ‘attributive name’.</span></span></span></div>    <div id="ring-links-box">
